WHITE PHOSPHORUS INTOXICATION - RUSSIA (STAVROPOL)
********************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail, a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: 24 Mar 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Mos News.com [edited]
<http://www.mosnews.com/news/2004/03/24/phosphor.shtml>

50 Hospitalized After Chemical Emission in Stavropol
--------------------------------------------------
50 people were hospitalized after chemical emissions caused a fire in the
southern Russian city of Stavropol Sunday, the Ministry of Emergency
Situations has reported.
The Ministry issued a statement describing how "as a result of exposure to
sunlight, on 21 Mar 2004 a container with chemical wasteÂ… leaked, emitting
50 kilograms of an unknown substance over an area of 70 square meters. The
substance caught fire."
The fire was put out that same day, and the unknown substance was
identified as highly toxic white phosphorus, Emergency Ministry said in a
statement.
Sergei Vlasov, a spokesman from the Emergency Ministry, told MosNews that
excavating work was carried out in the area in January 2004, and the
container was found underground. He said that it remains unknown why the
container was left standing out in the open. Another source from the
Ministry told MosNews that the container had been underground for at least
20 years near a railway station. He declined to say who might be held
responsible for the accident.
On Tuesday, a piece of phosphorus that had not been neutralized caught fire
again, and the fire was put out.
However, sources in the Emergency Ministry told MosNews that yet another
piece of phosphorus caught fire Wednesday, and that the fire is currently
being brought under control.
As a result of the accident 12 rescue workers and firemen were
hospitalized. The other 38 people were mostly police and by-standers
affected by the fire. 9 of the people have traces of phosphorus in their
blood and urine, a statement from the Emergency Ministry said.
A source from the Emergency Ministry speaking to MosNews on terms of
anonymity said, however, that no injuries were sustained from the accident.
Meanwhile, sources in the emergency room of the local hospital confirmed to
MosNews that 50 people were indeed hospitalized with injuries sustained in
the fire.
